[[Image:Three Makimuku kofun aerial view.jpg|thumb|200px|Katsuyama Kofun (top), Yazuka Kofun (bottom left), and Ishizuka Kofun (bottom right) within the {{ill|Makimuku Kofun Cluster|ja|纒向古墳群|qq=draft}} ({{ill|National Aerial Photography|ja|国土航空写真|qq=draft}})]]
'''Kofun Clusters''' (古墳群, ''Kofungun'') are groups of {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|qq=draft}}—ancient Kofuns—constituting a type of archaeological site.{{Sfn|Nara National Research Institute for Cultural Properties|2020|p=8}}
== Overview == Kofun rarely exist in isolation; it is more common for them to appear in groups of several to dozens of mounds, which are collectively referred to as "kofun clusters." Some clusters comprise hundreds of kofun. Notable examples include the {{ill|Mozu Kofun Cluster|ja|百舌鳥古墳群|1=Mozu Tombs|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Furuichi Kofun Cluster|ja|古市古墳群|qq=draft}} in Osaka Prefecture, the {{ill|Yamato Kofun Cluster|ja|大和古墳群|1=Ōyamato Kofun Group|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Makimuku Kofun Cluster|ja|纒向古墳群|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Saki Kofun Cluster|ja|佐紀盾列古墳群|1=Saki Tatenami Kofun group|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Umami Kofun Cluster|ja|馬見古墳群|1=Umami Kofun Cluster|qq=draft}} in Nara Prefecture, the {{ill|Iwase-Senzuka Kofun Cluster|ja|岩橋千塚古墳群|qq=draft}} in Wakayama Prefecture, and the {{ill|Saitobaru Kofun Cluster|ja|西都原古墳群|qq=draft}} in Miyazaki Prefecture.
When a kofun exists in isolation, unassociated with any cluster, it may be referred to as a "single Kofun" or ''tandokufun'' (単独墳). Within a kofun cluster, a particularly large or elaborate mound may be designated as a "principal mound" or ''meishufun'' (盟主墳), though these terms are used informally.
The arrangement and composition of kofun clusters often reflect the cultural, political, or geographical characteristics of the regions in which they are located.
