== Overview == Kofun rarely exist in isolation; it is more common for them to appear in groups of several to dozens of mounds, which are collectively referred to as "kofun clusters." Some clusters comprise hundreds of kofun. Notable examples include the [[:en:Mozu Tombs|Mozu Tombs]] and [[:en:Furuichi Kofun Cluster|Furuichi Kofun Cluster]] in Osaka Prefecture, the {{ill|Yamato Kofun Cluster|ja|大和古墳群|1=Ōyamato Kofun Cluster|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Kofun Cluster|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamato Kofun Cluster|qq=}}, [[:en:Makimuku Kofun Cluster|Makimuku Kofun Cluster]], {{ill|Saki Kofun Cluster|ja|佐紀盾列古墳群|1=Saki Tatenami Kofun group|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saki Kofun Cluster|13=User:Immanuelle/Saki Tatenami Kofun group|qq=}}, and {{ill|Umami Kofun Cluster|ja|馬見古墳群|1=Umami Kofun Cluster|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Umami Kofun Cluster|13=User:Immanuelle/Umami Kofun Cluster|qq=}} in Nara Prefecture, the [[:en:Iwase-Senzuka Kofun Cluster|Iwase-Senzuka Kofun Cluster]] in Wakayama Prefecture, and the [[:en:Saitobaru Kofun Cluster|Saitobaru Kofun Cluster]] in Miyazaki Prefecture.
When a kofun exists in isolation, unassociated with any cluster, it may be referred to as a "single Kofun" or ''tandokufun'' (単独墳). Within a kofun cluster, a particularly large or elaborate mound may be designated as a "principal mound" or ''meishufun'' (盟主墳), though these terms are used informally.
The arrangement and composition of kofun clusters often reflect the cultural, political, or geographical characteristics of the regions in which they are located.
